data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you used in .NET 10 (e.g., `EnableSyncOverAsync()`) no longer exists.

Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

## The fix

Convert all sync calls to their async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
| Sync (broken) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through all callers (controllers, services, etc.). The async methods live in `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` namespace — make sure `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;` is present.
